The organised labour in Adamawa State has threatened to embark on strike action if no agreement is reached in the ongoing negotiations on consequential adjustment between it and the state government. Labour said it has given the state government additional grace period of one week to the closing hours of Tuesday 25 Feb. 2020 to conclude and sign agreement with it. It warned that at the expiration of this notice, the organised labour in the state would have no option than to mobilise its members to proceed without further notice on indefinite strike action. A bulletin from the organised labour made available to newsmen yesterday in Yola, said the government has up to Feb. 18 to reach an agreement with the organised labour or face strike action. The statement indicated that the organised labour had met three times with government with the last meeting held on Tuesday, February 18. “We have made the government to understand the level of sacrifice that workers can offer in this regard. “The trade union side once more has given the state government additional grace period of one week to the closing hours of Tuesday 25 Feb. 2020 to conclude and sign agreement. “At the expiration of this notice, the organised labour in the state will have no option than to mobilise her members to proceed without further notice on indefinite strike action,” the bulletin said. It urged Adamawa workers to remain calm and law abiding as they wait for further directives. 